        "text": "# Communication is autopoietic"
      },
      "date": 1509637043431
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "3a21c9dfce9cbdb8",
        "text": "On the other hand, Luhmann explicitly stressed that he does not refer to a \"society without humans\", but to the fact that communication is autopoietic, in the sense that communicative actions result to communicative actions, that is communication manifests itself only as communication (communication results in more communication, or the end of communication thereof)."
      },
      "after": "fcefffe5c4f1dd2a",
      "id": "3a21c9dfce9cbdb8",
      "date": 1509637047242
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "c5940b94-da1e-4f54-9fb8-502e04c5d4c1",
        "text": "Luhmann likens the operation of autopoiesis (the filtering and processing of information from the environment) to a program ([[program (management)]]), making a series of logical distinctions (in German, ''Unterscheidungen''). Here, Luhmann refers to the British mathematician [[G. Spencer-Brown]]'s logic of distinctions that Maturana and Varela had earlier identified as a model for the functioning of any cognitive process. The supreme criterion guiding the \"self-creation\" of any given system is a defining [[binary code]]. This binary code, is not to be confused with the computers operation: Luhmann (following Spencer-Brown and [[Gregory Bateson]]) assumes that auto-referential systems are continuously confronted with the dilemma of disintegration/continuation. This dilemma is framed with an ever-changing set of available choices; everyone of those potential choices can be the system's selection or not (a binary state, selected/rejected). The influence of Spencer-Brown's book, ''[[Laws of Form]]'', on Luhmann can hardly be overestimated."
      },
      "after": "3a21c9dfce9cbdb8",
      "id": "c5940b94-da1e-4f54-9fb8-502e04c5d4c1",
      "date": 1509637052452
